               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-1129" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1129" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1129" type="surname" value="HIGHLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1129" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS HIGHLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Daniel William Saunders, a publican, at Rotherhithe—on the 31st of May, at half-past eleven o'clock I re<lb></lb>ceived information—I went out and saw the prisoner—I asked her if she would allow me to look under her shawl—she did, and I found one quart pot—I was taking her back, and going along she dropped two other pots—they were all my masters—she had no business with either of them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-1130" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1130" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1130" type="surname" value="LEARY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1130" type="given" value="TIMOTHY"></interp>TIMOTHY LEARY</persName>
                  </hi>. I was standing outside the window—I saw the prisoner sitting on the seat—I saw her take one pot and put it under her shawl—I told the potman of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> On the 31st of May I went to Deptford to purchase some articles—I met some friends who had come from Woolwich—we had some ale, and as I had nothing to eat since the morning, the ale made me unable to see—I did not know what I was doing—my friend before starting from me would make me have a drop of rum—they then went home—I had a small basket with some eatables in it—it had no handles, so I carried it in my apron—I fell asleep—I was not sober—I still kept my apron up—I got up and took</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184706140206"></xptr>
               <p>a pot which was on the table and was going to the ditch to fetch some water—when I got half way, the potboy came and took the pot out of my hand—he asked what I had got in my apron—I showed my basket—he said, "No, you have got a pot"—he took me back, and after I had passed some persons who were drinking, I saw a man throw a pot off the table, and he said to the boy "There is another for you"—he went and took it—I told him he ought to be ashamed to do it—he said I should pay for all—I cannot account for the post being in my apron, except some boys put it in.</p>
               <p>
